I‚Äôm going to self-nominate our (3128) robot from this year. We very intentionally chose an architecture that was easily compatible with a climb and minimized both stacked and total DoFs. We ended up with a strong performing robot that pretty easily qualified for champs (regional points system is amazing) and performed well at higher levels, too. We only have 7 motors outside of the drive train and a max stacked DoF of 1.5-2 (depending on how you count elevators).

We‚Äôre planning to build a 1778 robot in the off-season as it‚Äôs a slight stretch above our in-season robot but still achievable for us.

Sometimes ‚Äúupping your game‚Äù can mean doing less. Many teams try to do everything and end up not really perfecting any of them

9245 is one of my favorites of the season. They built a pretty effective and simple robot that filled it‚Äôs role perfectly. No L4, no barge, just a single stage elevator and a funnel to score L2/3 faster than most anyone. In terms of ‚Äúachievable‚Äù robots it‚Äôs hard to beat how simple and effective their design was.

Easy answer for me. Team 5409 - Chargers out of Oakville, Ontario. Averaged 22 pieces of coral per match at Provincials, including 3.4 pieces in auto. No ground coral intake, no algae scoring, no deep climb, yet still finished the year ranked 24th in the world in EPA. This robot was so much simpler than most robots in the world, and statistically better than 99.3% of all robots. There are many lessons to be learned from them.

4451‚Äôs offshoot team 4864 was the kitbot, perfected. They started the season with a kitbot on brushless that had a PhotonVision-based system and a pretty slick servo-based gap filler ramp for the scoring end. Alliance 4 captain and round 3 the first time out? Not bad.

By state, they‚Äôd added a deep climber using a similarly trick trap door and an Everybot climber. They were the most refined kitbot in the state to the eye test, and Statbotics backs that up (EPA of 31.9; next kitbot down was 9571 at 24.8).
